# Documentation Sync

After any significant code change, update relevant documentation:

## What triggers a docs update

- New feature or module added
- API endpoint added/changed/removed
- Data model changed
- Configuration options changed
- Dependencies added/removed
- Architecture decisions made

## Files to check

| Change Type | Update These |
|-------------|--------------|
| New feature | `README.md` (Features section), `docs/planning.md` |
| API change | `README.md` (if public-facing), `docs/api.md` (when it exists) |
| Architecture | `docs/planning.md`, `BLUEPRINT.md` |
| Dependencies | `backend/requirements.txt`, `frontend/package.json` |
| Scope change | `README.md` (Current Scope section) |

## How to update

1. Mark completed items in roadmap checklists with `[x]`
2. Add new planned items as `[ ]`
3. Update tech stack tables if dependencies change
4. Keep `BLUEPRINT.md` current with actual implementation state

## Don't update docs for

- Minor refactors that don't change behavior
- Bug fixes (unless they reveal a limitation worth documenting)
- Code style changes
